data.content:
Three things break in EF Core 10. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction code won't compile. Replace it with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

All that `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery is no longer needed — the API now accepts `Action<SetPropertyCalls<Blog>>`, so you can use normal C# control flow.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**Duplicate property names are uniquified.** Since both `ShippingAddress` and `BillingAddress` have a `Street` property, EF 10 will append a number to disambiguate. A migration will try to rename columns.

**Nested complex types use the full path.** Your `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` will now map to column `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of `BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix:** Pin the old column names explicitly so no migration rename is generated:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
            // ... other properties
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods like `CommandReaderExecuting` now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. Your code won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter (redacted SQL for logging)
    {
        // Use logCommandText for safe logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **every** method in the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.

---

**Summary:** The `ExecuteUpdateAsync` change is the biggest win — it eliminates ~15 lines of fragile expression-tree code. The other two are mechanical signature/config fixes.
